  <context>
    <background>
      Task 030 is the **integration evidence layer** for the Insights tool work
      shipped by tasks 024â€“029. It is the binding evidence layer for spec.md
      SC-11 (registered tool + both response paths render correctly) and SC-18
      (SME walkthrough signoff). Without this task's evidence, Phase 2 cannot
      close â€” SC-11 and SC-18 are explicit success criteria, not aspirational
      goals.

      The Wave D7 synthetic test entities (matter
      `da116923-d65a-f111-a825-3833c5d9bcb1`, project
      `27845394-8e5f-f111-a825-70a8a59455f4`, invoice
      `05c8ef8d-8e5f-f111-a825-70a8a59455f4`) were reserved by the Insights
      Engine r2 team specifically for cross-project consumer validation. They
      are tagged with practice-area metadata so the same three entities can
      drive 15 questions across CTRNS / IPPAT / BNKF. The integration brief Â§8
      bullet 8 names them explicitly. Using these entities (rather than
      arbitrary real-customer GUIDs) is the binding test-data choice â€” it
      avoids customer-data exposure and produces deterministic, reviewable
      evidence.

      The 5-questions-per-practice-area structure is borrowed from the
      `INSIGHTS-PLAYBOOK-VS-RAG-DECISION-TREE.md` decision-tree guide, which
      already contains 15 worked examples across CTRNS / IPPAT / BNKF. Those
      worked examples are calibrated for the playbook-vs-RAG decision
      boundary â€” they naturally exercise both response paths, plus the
      classifier vs `forceMode` decision branch. Reusing this calibration
      (rather than inventing fresh question text) anchors the smoke matrix to
      a peer-reviewed reference and aligns the cross-project narrative.

      The SME walkthrough is a soft acceptance test â€” it asks a legal-ops
      practitioner to judge "would this be useful in my actual work?"
      categorically per question and per practice area. The SME's role is
      qualitative judgment, NOT contract conformance (the integration tests
      assert contract conformance independently). SME signoff is binding per
      SC-18 â€” without it, the task cannot close. If no SME is available within
      the execution window, the task is BLOCKED pending SME availability â€”
      operator schedules and the task re-opens to close the loop.

      Information-leakage discipline (ADR-018 + integration brief Â§5.2) is
      load-bearing during evidence capture. The synthetic entities make this
      easy (no real customer data is at risk) but the discipline is
      reinforced here so the muscle memory carries into future tasks that may
      touch real-customer data. Question text and citation source names are
      OK to record verbatim; response answer text and citation excerpt text
      are paraphrased.

      Rate-limit considerations: aggregate budget is 60/min/oid across
      `/ask` + `/search` + `/assistant/query` per integration brief Â§11. Fifteen
      questions paced across at least 1 minute (~4s gap) stays well under
      budget. If smoke testing accidentally trips the 429 budget, that's a
      POSITIVE end-to-end validation of the rate-limit handling shipped by
      task 029 â€” log it as evidence, not as a failure.

      Cross-tool disambiguation observation: the Phase 2 verification suite
      (task 031) explicitly tests `/summarize` vs `insights.query` routing
      disambiguation. Task 030's SME walkthrough may surface disambiguation
      oddities (e.g., SME asks "summarize this matter" â€” does the agent route
      to `/summarize` or `insights.query`?). These observations are NOT
      pass/fail for task 030; they feed task 031's design AND the R6 backlog.

      After task 030 completes, task 031 runs the consolidated Phase 2
      end-to-end + cross-tool verification. After 030 + 031 ship, Phase 2
      closes and the project transitions to Phase 3.
    </background>
